        <section id="part-i" aria-labelledby="part-i-heading">
          <h2 id="part-i-heading">Part I: how Argentina became independent</h2>

          <h3 id="before-1810">Before 1810: a viceroyalty, not "Argentina"</h3>
          <p>
            The schoolbook story often starts in May 1810. The institutional background starts earlier. In 1776 the Spanish Crown created the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Viceroyalty_of_the_R%C3%ADo_de_la_Plata" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Viceroyalty of the Río de la Plata</a> with Buenos Aires as capital, grouping jurisdictions that today cover Argentina, Uruguay, Paraguay and Bolivia. Ternavasio notes that this was not yet a natural Argentine unit: it was a heterogeneous imperial space with changing borders and competing territorial loyalties.
          </p>
          <p>
            The <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/British_invasions_of_the_River_Plate" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">British invasions of 1806–1807</a> matter because they exposed the weakness of Spanish authority and militarized Buenos Aires society. The city defended itself, gained political confidence and grew used to acting on its own before the formal May Revolution. Ternavasio also notes that Buenos Aires still behaved more like the center of a local governorship than the real capital of a huge integrated viceroyalty, until May 1810 forced it to try to command that space.
          </p>
          <figure class="article-figure article-figure--map">
            <Picture
              src={viceroyaltyImage}
              formats={["avif", "webp"]}
              widths={[480, 720, 960, 1200]}
              sizes="(min-width: 72rem) 67ch, calc(100vw - 2rem)"
              alt="Map showing the Viceroyalty of the Río de la Plata in 1795 across southern South America."
              loading="lazy"
              decoding="async"
            />
            <figcaption>
              The Viceroyalty of the Río de la Plata in 1795, the imperial frame that 1810–1816 broke apart. Rasterized from TRAJAN 117, GFDL, via <a href="https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Viceroyalty_of_the_R%C3%ADo_de_la_Plata_(1795).svg" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Wikimedia Commons</a>.
            </figcaption>
          </figure>

          <h3 id="may-revolution">1810: autonomy, not independence</h3>
          <p>
            The chain of events began not in Buenos Aires but in Europe. In 1808 <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Napoleon" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Napoleon Bonaparte</a> invaded Spain, forced the abdications of Carlos IV and Fernando VII and installed his brother <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joseph_Bonaparte" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Joseph Bonaparte</a> on the Spanish throne. Spanish resistance juntas governed in Fernando's name; as they collapsed one by one, the legitimacy of colonial authorities in America collapsed with them. When news reached Buenos Aires in May 1810 that the Junta of Seville (the last major seat of Spanish resistance) had fallen, the criollos of Buenos Aires forced the issue.
          </p>
          <p>
            During the Semana de Mayo (18–25 May 1810), Buenos Aires removed Viceroy Baltasar Hidalgo de Cisneros and installed the Primera Junta, presided over by <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cornelio_Saavedra" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Cornelio Saavedra</a>. <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mariano_Moreno" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Mariano Moreno</a>, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Juan_Jos%C3%A9_Paso" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Juan José Paso</a> and <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Manuel_Belgrano" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Manuel Belgrano</a> were among the main figures.
          </p>
          <p>
            The Junta declared it governed "in the name of Sr. D. Fernando VII" (the famous "máscara de Fernando VII" / "mask of <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ferdinand_VII" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Ferdinand VII</a>"). The legal theory often invoked was <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Retroversion_of_sovereignty_to_the_people" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">retroversión de la soberanía</a>: with the king captive and the imperial order collapsing, sovereignty reverted to the <em>pueblos</em>. Ternavasio notes that "pueblo"/"pueblos" did not mean "the Argentine people" as a single nation; they could mean cities, provinces or local corporate communities claiming their own rights (<a href="https://www.conicet.gov.ar/repensar-la-independencia/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">CONICET / Ternavasio interview</a>). Early 1810 looks less like "Argentina vs Spain" and more like a fight over who had the right to govern the ruins of the old viceroyalty. Either way, no independence was declared in 1810. Educ.ar frames 9 July as the first explicit will of emancipation after the political process begun in May (<a href="https://www.educ.ar/recursos/132481/9-de-julio-dia-de-la-declaracion-de-la-independencia" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Educ.ar</a>).
          </p>

          <h3 id="buenos-aires-claim">Buenos Aires tries to inherit the viceroyalty</h3>
          <p>
            After May 1810, Ternavasio argues, Buenos Aires tried to make the old viceroyalty obey the revolutionary government seated in Buenos Aires and only then discovered what its capital claim actually required (support from jurisdictions it had not previously needed to command in the same way). That is why Paraguay, the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Banda_Oriental" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Banda Oriental</a> (roughly modern Uruguay), <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Upper_Peru" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Upper Peru</a> (modern Bolivia) and the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Argentine_Littoral" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Litoral</a> (the river provinces of northeastern Argentina) sit outside a single Argentine national story: Paraguay's autonomy became a point of no return; the Banda Oriental and Litoral tied themselves to the federal/confederal alternative of <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jos%C3%A9_Gervasio_Artigas" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Artigas</a>; Upper Peru remained militarily unstable.
          </p>
          <p>
            Ternavasio treats the early conflict as civil war as much as anti-Spanish war: communities, cities, provinces, royalists, autonomists, centralists and federalists fought inside the collapsing Spanish monarchy. The "patriots vs Spain" framing becomes available only later.
          </p>

          <h3 id="six-years">Six years of war and quarrel (1810–1816)</h3>
          <p>
            The years between were not a quiet wait for a decision already made. Belgrano fought in Paraguay, the Banda Oriental and the north; Spanish loyalists pushed back hard in Upper Peru; Fernando VII returned to the throne and tried to restore imperial control; and Artigas's Liga Federal broke with Buenos Aires. By early 1816 the revolution faced royalist pressure, Portuguese pressure and civil conflict, which made formal independence harder to postpone.
          </p>

          <h3 id="why-tucuman">Why Tucumán and not Buenos Aires</h3>
          <p>
            The provinces wanted a Congress outside Buenos Aires. Tucumán was inland, militarily safer and less identified with the port city's centralism. Choosing it signaled that independence would be a provincial decision, not another order from Buenos Aires.
          </p>
          <p>
            The Congress still did not represent every territory Buenos Aires hoped to inherit. It included interior and Alto Perú deputies, while the Litoral under Artigas, the Banda Oriental and Paraguay stayed out.
          </p>
          <figure class="article-figure article-figure--map article-figure--portrait">
            <Picture
              src={provinciasUnidasImage}
              formats={["avif", "webp"]}
              widths={[360, 540, 764]}
              sizes="(min-width: 48rem) 30rem, calc(100vw - 2rem)"
              alt="Approximate 1816 map of the United Provinces in South America, including areas beyond modern Argentina."
              loading="lazy"
              decoding="async"
            />
            <figcaption>
              Approximate 1816 map of the United Provinces, useful mainly for showing how much the claim exceeded modern Argentina. Adapted from Misteruploader, CC BY-SA 4.0, via <a href="https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Provincias_Unidas.png" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Wikimedia Commons</a>.
            </figcaption>
          </figure>

          <h3 id="san-martin">San Martín's pressure and the "juridical" argument for independence</h3>
          <p>
            From Mendoza, where he was organizing the Army of the Andes, San Martín pressed the Congress to stop fighting as nominal vassals of the king. In an April 1816 letter to <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tom%C3%A1s_Godoy_Cruz" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Tomás Godoy Cruz</a>, he mocked the contradiction: "How long are we going to wait to declare our independence!" The declaration was a military necessity as much as a legal act.
          </p>

          <h3 id="session-9-july">The session of 9 July 1816</h3>
          <p>
            On 9 July 1816, the deputies met in the house of <a href="https://es.wikipedia.org/wiki/Francisca_Baz%C3%A1n_de_Laguna" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Francisca Bazán de Laguna</a>. President <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Francisco_Narciso_de_Laprida" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Francisco Narciso de Laprida</a> put the independence question to the room and the deputies answered yes. The <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Argentine_Declaration_of_Independence" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Acta de la Independencia</a> declared the provinces' will to break ties with the kings of Spain and become a free nation independent of Ferdinand VII, his successors and metropolis.
          </p>
          <figure class="article-figure article-figure--document">
            <Picture
              src={actaImage}
              formats={["avif", "webp"]}
              widths={[480, 720, 900, 1181]}
              sizes="(min-width: 72rem) 67ch, calc(100vw - 2rem)"
              alt="Printed Acta de la Independencia with the declaration text and signatures."
              loading="lazy"
              decoding="async"
            />
            <figcaption>
              A printed Acta of the declaration. Public domain, via <a href="https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Acta_de_la_independencia_de_los_pueblos_confederados_de_la_Rep%C3%BAblica_Argentina.jpg" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Wikimedia Commons</a>.
            </figcaption>
          </figure>

          <h3 id="foreign-domination">"…and of all other foreign domination": the 19 July addition</h3>
          <p>
            The 9 July text broke with Spain but said nothing about <em>other</em> powers. In the following days, rumors circulated that the Director Pueyrredón, General Belgrano and even some deputies were entertaining schemes to hand the country to Portugal (or, earlier, to Britain; Alvear had floated a British protectorate in 1815). Belgrano's own monarchy proposal fed these fears.
          </p>
          <p>
            A few days later, the Congress added "y de toda otra dominación extranjera", closing the door on rumors that the new state might be handed to Portugal or another power.
          </p>

          <h3 id="inca-monarchy">The monarchy-vs-republic debate and Belgrano's Inca prince</h3>
          <p>
            Independence did not settle the form of government. Constitutional monarchy still looked normal in post-Napoleonic Europe and Belgrano even proposed crowning a descendant of the Incas with the capital at Cuzco. San Martín, Güemes and Alto Perú deputies were sympathetic, but the plan collapsed under porteño elite opposition, no agreed candidate and racist objections. A durable republican constitution came only in 1853.
          </p>

          <h3 id="translations">The Acta in Spanish, Quechua and Aymara</h3>
          <p>
            The Congress ordered the Acta printed in Quechua and Aymara as well as Spanish, because the United Provinces still claimed Alto Perú and wanted the declaration to circulate beyond Spanish-speaking elites. A Guaraní version was proposed but not distributed while the Litoral was at war with Buenos Aires.
          </p>

          <h3 id="after-declaration">After the declaration: the wider Spanish-American context</h3>
          <p>
            In 1817 San Martín crossed the Andes and defeated royalist forces at Chacabuco. The army could now claim to fight for a declared sovereign state, not for rebels still pretending loyalty to the king.
          </p>
          <p>
            The Congress later approved a unitary constitution that failed, then dissolved after civil war. The declared "Provincias Unidas en Sud América" still bore little resemblance to today's Argentina: Alto Perú became Bolivia, while Uruguay's path to independence followed its own course.
          </p>

          <h3 id="regional-memory">Do neighbors celebrate this?</h3>
          <p>
            No neighboring country celebrates 9 July as its own national holiday. Chile and Peru remember parts of the same 1810s–1820s cycle positively, but through their own independence stories: in Chile, the crossing of the Andes and the battles of Chacabuco and Maipú are remembered as victories for Chilean and Argentine patriots, and San Martín and O'Higgins then organized the expedition to Peru (<a href="https://www.memoriachilena.gob.cl/602/w3-article-692.html" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Memoria Chilena</a>; <a href="https://www.memoriachilena.gob.cl/602/w3-article-93425.html" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">San Martín / Memoria Chilena</a>). That memory is not "Argentina intervened in us" so much as "a trans-Andean patriot army helped finish our war against Spain."
          </p>
          <p>
            The more suspicious memories are in places where Buenos Aires tried to inherit the old viceroyalty. Paraguay's independence narrative stresses that Buenos Aires wanted to keep Paraguay inside those borders and sent Belgrano after Paraguay refused; Paraguayan patriots defeated his expedition at Paraguarí and Tacuarí and sought independence from both Spain and Buenos Aires (<a href="https://www.abc.com.py/edicion-impresa/suplementos/escolar/14-y-15-de-mayo-de-1811-independencia-del-paraguay-1700751.html" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">ABC Color</a>). In the Banda Oriental, the Artiguist Protectorate built a federal alternative in opposition to Buenos Aires, so Uruguay's 1810s memory centers more on Artigas, local sovereignty and later Portuguese/Brazilian pressure than on Tucumán (<a href="https://www.redalyc.org/journal/3870/387052694006/html/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Frega</a>). Upper Peru sits between these cases: Charcas sent deputies to Tucumán, but Bolivia's later founding story is 1825, when the Alto Perú assembly chose not to join Argentina or Peru and declared its own state (<a href="https://www.educa.com.bo/independencia-de-bolivia/creacion-de-la-republica-de-bolivia-asamblea-constituyente" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Educa Bolivia</a>).
          </p>

          <h3 id="recognition">International recognition after 1816</h3>
          <p>
            Recognition lagged behind the declaration. The compressed timeline is: 1818, Bouchard's Hawaiʻi episode is often remembered as the first recognition but is better treated as an irregular ship-and-flag episode (see the note below); 1823, the United States recognized the Government of Buenos Ayres and opened diplomatic relations later that year (<a href="https://history.state.gov/countries/argentina" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">U.S. Office of the Historian</a>); 1825, Britain signed a Treaty of Friendship, Commerce and Navigation and recognized Argentina (<a href="https://history.blog.gov.uk/2016/08/18/britain-and-an-independent-south-america/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">UK History of Government</a>); 1863, Spain finally recognized Argentina through the Treaty of Recognition, Peace and Friendship (<a href="https://tratados.cancilleria.gob.ar/tratado_archivo.php?tratados_id=mKaklw==&tipo=kg==&id=laColg==&caso=pdf" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Cancillería treaty PDF</a>).
          </p>

          <h3 id="naming">The name "Argentina" comes later</h3>
          <p>
            In 1816 the relevant name was Provincias Unidas en Sud América. Ternavasio notes that "Sudamérica" itself expressed uncertainty about which provinces would actually fall under the new legal condition, especially since the Banda Oriental and Litoral did not sit in the Congress. The failed centralist constitution of 1826 used the label República Argentina and declared a representative republican form, but provincial rejection prevented a stable modern state (<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/United_Provinces_of_the_R%C3%ADo_de_la_Plata" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Wikipedia</a>; <a href="https://repositorio.uca.edu.ar/bitstream/123456789/10002/1/sobre-denominaciones-republica-argentina.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">UCA on denominations</a>). For Ternavasio, the history of the Argentine Republic begins <em>stricto sensu</em> only after Buenos Aires accepted the 1853 Constitution (after 1860).
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="part-ii" aria-labelledby="part-ii-heading">
          <h2 id="part-ii-heading">Part II: how the holiday evolved</h2>

          <h3 id="first-celebrations">The first celebrations and the 19th-century see-saw</h3>
          <p>
            Celebrations began immediately in Tucumán, but for much of the 19th century 25 May kept the stronger place in patriotic culture. Rivadavia even folded 9 July into the May festivities; Rosas later restored it to full rank and used both holidays for federal political theater.
          </p>

          <h3 id="casa-historica">The Casa Histórica: demolition, the Templete and the 1943 reconstruction</h3>
          <p>
            The famous "Casita" was not originally a tiny cottage but a substantial colonial <em>casona</em>. The state later demolished almost all of it, preserving the oath room inside a decorative pavilion called the Templete. That pavilion helped create the popular image of a little adobe house.
          </p>
          <p>
            The current Casa Histórica is a 1940s reconstruction based on old photographs and plans. Even its familiar schoolbook colors changed: later research restored white walls and blue openings rather than the yellow-and-green scheme many Argentines learned in school.
          </p>
          <figure class="article-figure">
            <Picture
              src={casaHistoricaImage}
              formats={["avif", "webp"]}
              widths={[640, 960, 1280, 1600, 2200]}
              sizes="(min-width: 72rem) 67ch, calc(100vw - 2rem)"
