              The present Casa Histórica in Tucumán, photographed in 2025 and resized from the original. Horacio Cambeiro, CC BY-SA 4.0, via <a href="https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Casa_Hist%C3%B3rica_de_la_Independencia_%E2%80%A2_Casa_de_Tucum%C3%A1n_(31147).jpg" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Wikimedia Commons</a>.
            </figcaption>
          </figure>

          <h3 id="centenario">The Centenario (1916): a subdued centennial</h3>
          <p>
            The 100th anniversary in 1916 was muted. World War I kept foreign guests away, President Victorino de la Plaza skipped Tucumán and the moment sat in the shadow of the more lavish 1910 May centenary.
          </p>
          <p>
            Balmaceda and others note an asymmetry that stuck: 25 May is remembered more vividly than 9 July in popular culture, partly because May 1810 has better-known protagonists in schoolbooks (<a href="https://www.lanacion.com.ar/lifestyle/por-que-recordamos-mas-revolucion-mayo-nid2265816/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">La Nación</a>).
          </p>

          <h3 id="peron-1947">Perón and the "Economic Independence" of 1947</h3>
          <p>
            On 9 July 1947, President Juan Domingo Perón staged an act of Independencia Económica at the Casa Histórica. It cast Peronist nationalizations and economic policy as a second emancipation, deliberately echoing 1816 (<a href="https://www.infobae.com/sociedad/2023/07/09/el-otro-congreso-de-tucuman-el-dia-que-peron-declaro-la-independencia-economica-y-auguro-60-anos-sin-crisis/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Infobae</a>).
          </p>

          <h3 id="sesquicentenario">The Sesquicentenario (1966) and the dictatorships</h3>
          <p>
            The 150th anniversary in 1966 was swallowed by politics: <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arturo_Umberto_Illia" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Arturo Illia</a> was overthrown days before the commemoration and the dictatorship reduced the anniversary to a military parade.
          </p>
          <p>
            In 1975, the Peronist government launched <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Operation_Independence" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Operativo Independencia</a>, a military campaign in Tucumán against the ERP. Its name and location still tie the holiday to Argentina's later memory politics.
          </p>

          <h3 id="modern-ritual">Modern commemoration: the standard ritual</h3>
          <p>
            Contemporary 9 July commemorations are usually centered on Tucumán and include:
          </p>
          <ul>
            <li>A presidential visit to Tucumán and the Casa Histórica (in most years);</li>
            <li>The Tedeum (Te Deum mass) in the Cathedral of San Miguel de Tucumán;</li>
            <li>The izamiento (flag raising) in Plaza Independencia;</li>
            <li>The "chocolate patrio" (hot chocolate shared in the plaza in the winter morning);</li>
            <li>A desfile cívico-militar (civic-military parade) with the armed forces, gaucho associations, indigenous communities, immigrant collectivities and schools;</li>
            <li>Nationwide Te Deums, school pageants and flag displays. Under <a href="https://www.argentina.gob.ar/normativa/nacional/ley-27399-281835/texto" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Ley 27.399</a> (2017), 9 July is listed among Argentina's feriados nacionales inamovibles (immovable national holidays).</li>
          </ul>
          <p>
            9 July falls in the depth of the southern winter, so the traditional food is warm and heavy: especially locro, plus empanadas, pastelitos, humita and tortas fritas. Locro is a slow-cooked Andean stew of maize, beans, squash and meat, now eaten on both national dates, 25 May and 9 July.
          </p>
          <p>
            The patriotic link is newer than the holiday itself: food historian Carina Perticone argues that locro became the dominant patriotic dish in Buenos Aires only in the 20th century (<a href="https://www.iprofesional.com/actualidad/339869-por-que-comemos-locro-el-25-de-mayo-te-dejamos-una-super-receta" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">iProfesional interview</a>).
          </p>

          <h3 id="bicentenario">The Bicentenario (2016)</h3>
          <p>
            On 9 July 2016, President <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mauricio_Macri" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Mauricio Macri</a> led the Bicentenario ceremonies in Tucumán, hosted Spain's emeritus king <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Juan_Carlos_I" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Juan Carlos I</a> and framed independence around Tucumán without mentioning May 1810, another example of the 1810/1816 conflation.
          </p>

          <h3 id="milei-years">The Milei years (2024–2026): politics returns to Tucumán</h3>
          <p>
            Under President <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Javier_Milei" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Javier Milei</a>, 9 July again became a stage for national politics, part of the long tradition of later governments reusing the date. On 9 July 2024 he signed the "Pacto de Mayo" with 18 governors in the Casa Histórica. In the official speech, he presented 1816 as the end of the revolution and the beginning of a new order for the Provincias Unidas, then claimed the same role for his own pact: "El 9 de julio de 2024, con la firma de este Acta de Mayo… anunciamos también el puntapié inicial de un nuevo orden" ("On 9 July 2024, with the signing of this Act of May... we also announce the starting point of a new order"; <a href="https://www.casarosada.gob.ar/informacion/discursos/50568-palabras-del-presidente-javier-milei-en-la-firma-del-pacto-de-mayo" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Casa Rosada, 9 July 2024</a>).
          </p>
          <p>
            In 2025 he cancelled the Tucumán vigilia. The government cited fog and flight conditions; only a handful of governors had confirmed attendance, a sharp contrast with the 2024 photo. He marked the day instead at the Campo Argentino de Polo in Buenos Aires (<a href="https://tn.com.ar/politica/2025/07/09/tras-cancelar-la-vigilia-del-9-de-julio-milei-conmemorara-la-independencia-en-el-campo-argentino-de-polo/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">TN</a>).
          </p>
          <p>
            In 2026 he returned to the Casa Histórica and leaned directly on the historical material that this article traces. He opened with San Martín's Army of the Andes line, "Seamos libres, y lo demás no importa nada" ("Let us be free, and the rest matters not"), then called his economic program "una suerte de cruce de los Andes en materia económica" ("a kind of Crossing of the Andes in economic affairs") and the moment "una especie de segunda Independencia" ("a kind of second independence"). He compared the colonial viceroyalty's failure toward the provinces with the modern national state's failure toward them, and likened his cabinet to "los librepensadores de 1816" ("the freethinkers of 1816"; <a href="https://www.casarosada.gob.ar/slider-principal/51309-discurso-del-presidente-javier-milei-por-el-210-aniversario-del-dia-de-la-independencia-en-la-casa-historica-de-tucuman" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Casa Rosada, 9 July 2026</a>). The "second independence" framing follows the same pattern as Perón's 1947 Independencia Económica: another government using Tucumán to claim a sequel to 1816.
          </p>
          <p>
            The period also brought a dispute over national museum leadership and budgets, with historians accusing the government of politicizing heritage institutions and the government saying it was removing ideological bias (<a href="https://noticias.perfil.com/noticias/cultura/controlar-el-relato-por-que-despidieron-al-director-del-museo-historico-nacional.phtml" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Perfil</a>).
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="notes" aria-labelledby="notes-heading">
          <h2 id="notes-heading">Common mix-ups</h2>
          <ul>
            <li>
              9 July 1816 ≠ the modern Argentine Republic. The Act declared the independence of the Provincias Unidas en Sud América, a larger entity that then included the Alto Perú. The name "Argentina" and today's territory consolidated later, especially after 1853–1860 (Ternavasio; <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/United_Provinces_of_the_R%C3%ADo_de_la_Plata" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Wikipedia</a>).
            </li>
            <li>
              May 1810 ≠ independence. 1810 was autonomy under the "mask of Ferdinand VII"; 1816 was formal independence and sovereignty. The conflation is common, including in presidential speeches (Macri in 2016).
            </li>
            <li>
              "Argentina vs Spain" is incomplete. Early conflict was also civil war inside the old imperial order: cities vs capital, provinces vs provinces, Americans vs peninsulares, federalists vs centralists (Ternavasio).
            </li>
            <li>
              July was not always the main patriotic holiday. May 25 had an earlier and often more privileged place; Fiestas Julias were added after 1816 (<a href="https://www.educ.ar/recursos/130924/un-pais-con-dos-fechas-patrias" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Educ.ar / Ternavasio</a>).
            </li>
            <li>
              The Congress did not speak for all of modern Argentina. The Litoral under Artigas stayed out; Charcas (today Bolivia) sent deputies (<a href="https://www.educ.ar/recursos/132481/9-de-julio-dia-de-la-declaracion-de-la-independencia" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Educ.ar</a>).
            </li>
            <li>
              Independence did not settle republicanism. Constitutional monarchy, including Belgrano's Inca proposal, was seriously debated; it failed for political and social reasons, not because it was a joke (<a href="https://elhistoriador.com.ar/el-congreso-de-tucuman-y-la-declaracion-de-la-independencia-por-felipe-pigna/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">El Historiador</a>).
            </li>
            <li>
              The Hawaiʻi recognition story is half-true. A great trivia version says the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hawaiian_Kingdom" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Kingdom of Hawaiʻi</a> was the first state to recognize Argentine independence. The real episode is stranger: in 1818 the Argentine privateer <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hippolyte_Bouchard" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Hipólito Bouchard</a> reached Hawaiʻi, found a mutinied Argentine ship that had been sold to <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kamehameha_I" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Kamehameha I</a> and negotiated its return. Bartolomé Mitre later treated the agreement as Argentina's first international treaty; the narrower reading is that Bouchard solved a ship-and-flag dispute, not that Hawaiʻi opened normal diplomatic relations. So: funny, not invented from nothing, but not normal state recognition either (<a href="https://imagesofoldhawaii.com/provincias-unidas-del-rio-de-la-plata-united-provinces-of-the-river-plate/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Images of Old Hawaiʻi</a>; <a href="https://www.nuestromar.org/el-cap-bouchard-y-como-se-reconocio-por-primera-vez-la-independencia-argentina/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Nuestro Mar</a>).
            </li>
            <li>
              "Casita" and yellow-green walls. The house was a large colonial <em>casona</em>; the tiny-cottage image comes mainly from the 1904 Templete. Today's museum building is a 1943 reconstruction. School yellow-and-green colors come from a 19th-century painting; a 1996 study found white walls with Prussian-blue openings for 1816.
            </li>
          </ul>
        </section>
      </article>

      <article class="article language-panel" lang="es-AR" data-language-panel="es" hidden>
        <section id="resumen" aria-labelledby="resumen-heading">
          <h2 id="resumen-heading">Panorama</h2>
          <p>
            El 9 de julio es el Día de la Independencia argentina: un feriado nacional de invierno que conmemora la declaración hecha en San Miguel de Tucumán el 9 de julio de 1816 por el Congreso de Tucumán. Los diputados declararon a las <a href="https://es.wikipedia.org/wiki/Provincias_Unidas_del_R%C3%ADo_de_la_Plata" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Provincias Unidas en Sud América</a> (una entidad política que reclamaba más territorio que la Argentina actual) independientes de España; días después agregaron la ruptura con toda otra dominación extranjera (<a href="https://www.educ.ar/recursos/132481/9-de-julio-dia-de-la-declaracion-de-la-independencia" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Educ.ar</a>; <a href="https://es.wikipedia.org/wiki/Declaraci%C3%B3n_de_independencia_de_la_Argentina" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Acta / Wikipedia</a>). Bajo la <a href="https://www.argentina.gob.ar/normativa/nacional/ley-27399-281835/texto" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Ley 27.399</a> (2017), la fecha es feriado nacional inamovible.
          </p>
          <p>
            Las conmemoraciones oficiales suelen centrarse en Tucumán y la <a href="https://www.argentina.gob.ar/capital-humano/cultura/monumentos/museo-casa-historica-de-la-independencia" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Casa Histórica</a>: Te Deum, izamiento de la bandera, desfile cívico-militar, presencia presidencial en la mayoría de los años. En todo el país se comen platos de invierno, sobre todo locro, y las escuelas hacen actos y banderas. La Argentina también conserva el 25 de mayo (Revolución de Mayo de 1810) como gran fecha patria; las dos se mencionan juntas y a veces se confunden (<a href="https://www.lanacion.com.ar/lifestyle/por-que-recordamos-mas-revolucion-mayo-nid2265816/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">La Nación</a>). El historiador <a href="https://www.lanacion.com.ar/cultura/25-de-mayo-preguntas-y-respuestas-para-entender-los-sucesos-de-una-semana-historica-nid19052021/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Daniel Balmaceda</a> resume la diferencia como autonomía en 1810 versus independencia y soberanía en 1816.
          </p>
          <p>
            El resto de esta página cuenta cómo se llegó a la declaración, quiénes quedaron adentro y afuera, cómo recuerdan países vecinos el mismo ciclo revolucionario, cuándo fue reconocida la independencia en el exterior, cómo cambió después la fiesta y las confusiones habituales. Gobiernos posteriores reutilizaron el 9 de julio (<a href="https://es.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bernardino_Rivadavia" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Rivadavia</a> 1826, <a href="https://es.wikipedia.org/wiki/Juan_Manuel_de_Rosas" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Rosas</a> 1835, <a href="https://es.wikipedia.org/wiki/Juan_Domingo_Per%C3%B3n" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Perón</a> 1947, Operativo Independencia 1975, administraciones recientes). La propia Casa Histórica fue demolida en gran parte en 1903–04 y reconstruida en 1943.
          </p>
